<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-240-771  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 240 771.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Jan 9 1989 v11 n2 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Security of fiber-optic networks is in doubt.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stephens, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic cables were once thought to be very secure, butexperts now say that any fiber network can now be tapped.andO;Northern Telecom Inc's John Saladna says that tapping afiber-optic cable requires stripping the cable's plastic outersheathing and gaining access to the glass fibers within.andP;  Thecable must then be bent 180 degrees around a one-eighth-inchradius forcing the light to travel around on a tighter bend thanit is capable of traversing without some loss of light.andP;  Thisescaping light is then detected and demultiplexed.andP;  Fiber systemstypically allow a 10-db loss before sounding an alarm.andP;  Loweringthis to 3-db or using air-core cables allows security breaches tobe detected fairly easily.andP;  Fiber is still much more secure thanother media, such as coax or twisted pair.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsCablesSecurityCommunications Tapping.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   How to tap a fiber-optic cable. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>